<p>I want to do something simple (or so I thought) using XSLT. I want to split a list of elements to two, rename an element using  The idea is that a xml formed like this:</p>  <pre><code>&lt;elem at="value" id="something"/&gt; &lt;elem at="value" id="something2"/&gt; &lt;elem at="random" id="something3"/&gt; </code></pre>  <p>will be converted to:</p>  <pre><code>&lt;elemVal id="something"/&gt; &lt;elemVal id="something2"/&gt; &lt;elemRa id="something3"/&gt; </code></pre>  <p>(the  new element names are static) So the elements are renamed based on the value of an attribute.</p>  <pre><code>&lt;xsl:template match="node()|@*"&gt;     &lt;xsl:copy&gt;         &lt;xsl:apply-templates select="node()|@*" /&gt;     &lt;/xsl:copy&gt; &lt;/xsl:template&gt;  &lt;xsl:template match="elem/@at[.='value']"&gt;     &lt;xsl:element name="elemVa"&gt;         &lt;xsl:apply-templates select="node()|@*"/&gt;     &lt;/xsl:element&gt; &lt;/xsl:template&gt; </code></pre>  <p>So far I have an identity template, but I don't understand how I can go backwards and change the elements name, keeping it's content.</p>